The failure is caused by a classic stack buffer overflow in:

```c
/root/chatdbgpro/bench/cases/external/crashbench-abo2/program.c
```

Relevant source:

```c
7  int main(int argv,char **argc) {
8          char buf[256];
9
10         strcpy(buf,argc[1]);
11         exit(1);
12 }
```

The command line was:

```sh
./build/prog AAAAAAAAAA...AAAA
```

with an argument much longer than 256 bytes.

At runtime:

```c
int main(int argv, char **argc)
```

Here the parameter names are misleading:

- `argv` is actually the argument count, conventionally named `argc`.
- `argc` is actually the argument vector, conventionally named `argv`.

So for the failing command:

```c
argv == 2
argc[0] == "./build/prog"
argc[1] == "AAAA....AAAA"
```

Then line 10 executes:

```c
strcpy(buf, argc[1]);
```

`buf` is a fixed-size stack buffer:

```c
char buf[256];
```

`strcpy` copies bytes until and including the terminating `'\0'`. Therefore, `buf` can safely hold at most 255 non-NUL characters plus the terminator.

The supplied argument is far longer than that. If the input has, for example, 512 `A` characters, then `strcpy` attempts to copy:

```c
512 + 1 == 513 bytes
```

into:

```c
256 bytes
```

That writes roughly 257 bytes past the end of `buf`.

Because `buf` is a stack allocation, the overflow corrupts adjacent stack memory. Depending on compiler options and layout, that can overwrite stack redzones, saved frame data, the saved return address, or other local/metadata values. This binary appears to contain sanitizer instrumentation/interceptors, so the overwrite may be caught immediately as a stack-buffer-overflow rather than later through a corrupted return address.

The immediate defective statement is line 10:

```c
strcpy(buf, argc[1]);
```

It performs an unbounded copy from attacker-controlled command-line input into a fixed-size stack buffer.

There is also a secondary robustness issue: the code assumes `argc[1]` exists. If the program is run with no extra argument, `argc[1]` would be `NULL`, and `strcpy(buf, NULL)` would also be invalid.

The final `exit(1)` is not the root cause of the memory corruption, though it does mean the program always exits with failure status even when no overflow occurs.

##### Minimal local fix

Replace the unbounded `strcpy` with a bounded copy and check that an argument was supplied.

For example:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>

int main(int argc, char **argv) {
    char buf[256];

    if (argc < 2) {
        fprintf(stderr, "usage: %s <string>\n", argv[0]);
        return 1;
    }

    snprintf(buf, sizeof buf, "%s", argv[1]);

    return 0;
}
```

This prevents writing past `buf`. `snprintf` always NUL-terminates as long as `sizeof buf > 0`.

If truncation should be treated as an error instead of silently accepted:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>

int main(int argc, char **argv) {
    char buf[256];

    if (argc < 2) {
        fprintf(stderr, "usage: %s <string>\n", argv[0]);
        return 1;
    }

    if (strlen(argv[1]) >= sizeof buf) {
        fprintf(stderr, "input too long: maximum is %zu bytes\n", sizeof buf - 1);
        return 1;
    }

    strcpy(buf, argv[1]);

    return 0;
}
```

This preserves the same fixed-size stack buffer design but rejects inputs that cannot fit.

##### More thorough root-cause fix

The deeper problem is that the program uses a fixed-size local buffer for arbitrary-length external input. If the program does not actually require a 256-byte limit, allocate storage sized to the input instead:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>

int main(int argc, char **argv) {
    char *buf;

    if (argc < 2) {
        fprintf(stderr, "usage: %s <string>\n", argv[0]);
        return 1;
    }

    buf = malloc(strlen(argv[1]) + 1);
    if (buf == NULL) {
        perror("malloc");
        return 1;
    }

    strcpy(buf, argv[1]);

    /*
       Use buf here.
    */

    free(buf);
    return 0;
}
```

Or, more simply on POSIX systems:

```c
char *buf = strdup(argv[1]);
if (buf == NULL) {
    perror("strdup");
    return 1;
}
```

The root-cause fix is to stop copying unchecked external input into a fixed-size stack buffer. Either validate the input length before copying, or allocate a destination buffer large enough for the supplied input.

##### Recommendation

Fix `/root/chatdbgpro/bench/cases/external/crashbench-abo2/program.c`, line 10.

Minimal safe replacement:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>

int main(int argc, char **argv) {
    char buf[256];

    if (argc < 2) {
        fprintf(stderr, "usage: %s <string>\n", argv[0]);
        return 1;
    }

    if (strlen(argv[1]) >= sizeof buf) {
        fprintf(stderr, "input too long\n");
        return 1;
    }

    strcpy(buf, argv[1]);
    return 0;
}
```

More thorough fix: avoid the fixed-size stack buffer and dynamically allocate `strlen(argv[1]) + 1` bytes before copying.

